article.headline: Griffith has 17 points, 13 boards in loss
article.linkText: Fever top Monarchs to move a game above .500
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Tamika Catchings is happy to contribute
without scoring as much as she's used to.

Indiana's All-Star forward had 18 points and a season-high seven
assists to lead the Fever past the Sacramento Monarchs 63-50
Wednesday night.

"Teams are playing me differently and the team differently,"
Catchings said. "I'm focusing on driving and putting my teammates
in position to score.

Catchings, whose scoring average of 16.4 points is her lowest in
three seasons, leads the Fever with 37 assists.

She had five steals as the Monarchs committed a season-high 20
turnovers with guard Ticha Penicheiro hampered by a bruised left
hand.

The injury kept Penicheiro out of the starting lineup for the
first time in three seasons. She played only 20 minutes, failed to
score and had a season-low two assists with two turnovers.

Penicheiro is one assist from tying Teresa Weatherspoon of the
Los Angeles Sparks as the WNBA's career leader.

Indiana never trailed with Deanna Jackson scoring 10 points and
reserve Kristen Rasmussen contributing 11 points.

Yolanda Griffith led the Monarchs with 17 points and 13
rebounds, the 70th double-double in her six-season career. DeMya
Walker added 11 points for Sacramento, which fell to a league-worst
2-6.

"We just couldn't throw it in the ocean," Sacramento coach
John Whisenant said. "We're not a great perimeter shooting team to
begin with and now we're missing shots that we shouldn't be missing
down low."

The 50 points by Sacramento were the fewest allowed by Indiana
this season, and the Monarchs' shooting percentage of 35.1 was the
lowest by an Indiana opponent this year.
